The crude theaflavin extract was measured to quantitate the yield of each extraction with the Indian source of tea yielding the highest quantity of crude extract. Each of the extracts was then examined by HPLC. The chromatograms of the crude extracts showed the same four peaks: TF1, TF2A, TF2B, and TF3 at the expected retention times of 14–16, 22–25, 27–30, and 32–36 min and in addition, multiple peaks prior to peaks TF1 through TF3 which we refer to as initial peaks (Fig. 1
). The initial peaks are suspected to be theaflavin-like substances but as of now they remain uncharacterized. The U.S. source of tea was selected for additional studies. After fractionation of each of the peaks TF1 through TF3 of this source, each individual fraction was evaluated by HPLC again to verify that each sample was pure. Proposed chemical structures of TF1, TF2A, TF2B, and TF3 are shown in Fig. 2
(Takino et al., 1965).
